QUESTION 4: Determine the correlation between two variables sat_avg and median_debt

4.1 Find the p-values

#4.1Find the p-values
library("ggpubr") 
ggscatter(college, x = "sat_avg", y = "median_debt", 
          add = "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE, 
          cor.coef = TRUE, cor.method = "pearson",
          xlab = "Score", ylab = "Amount")

shapiro.test(college$sat_avg)
shapiro.test(college$median_debt)
#p value is tiny, so yes we can state p to be significant.

4.2 Visualization and conclusion of the correlation with scatterplots

# Scatterplots
library("ggpubr") 
# sat_avg
ggqqplot(college$sat_avg, ylab = "Score")

# median_debt
ggqqplot(college$median_debt, ylab = "Amount")

res <- cor.test(college$sat_avg, college$median_debt, 
                    method = "pearson")
res

# Extract the p.value
res$p.value

# Extract the correlation coefficient
res$estimate

#CONCLUSION: The p-value of the test is 4.680179e-22, which is less than the significance level alpha = 0.05. We can conclude that sat_avg and median_debt are significantly correlated with a correlation coefficient of -0.27 and p-value of 4.680179e-22.So when the college are having higher SAT score, the students tend to manage the finance much better, meaning that the debt is low.

QUESTION 8: Distribution of the highest degree in universities ?

m = read.csv("college.csv", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE, na.strings = "")
summary(m[,c(5:8)])
##     region          highest_degree       control             gender         
##  Length:1269        Length:1269        Length:1269        Length:1269       
##  Class :character   Class :character   Class :character   Class :character  
##  Mode  :character   Mode  :character   Mode  :character   Mode  :character
dist_data<-data.frame(category=c("Associate","Bachelor","Graduate"),#build the data frame
                  count=c(20,200,1049))
dist_data$fraction = dist_data$count / sum(dist_data$count)#calculate the percentage
dist_data$ymax = cumsum(dist_data$fraction)
dist_data$ymin = c(0, head(dist_data$ymax, n=-1))
dist_data$labelPosition <- (dist_data$ymax + dist_data$ymin) / 2 #position of the label 
dist_data$label <- paste0(dist_data$category, "\n ", dist_data$count,"\n","(",round(dist_data$fraction*100,1),"%)")
ggplot(dist_data, aes(ymax=ymax, ymin=ymin, xmax=4, xmin=3, fill=category)) +
  geom_rect() +#draw the plot as rectangle
  geom_text( x=1.8, aes(y=labelPosition, label=label, color=category), size=3.5) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette=12) +#color of fillment
  scale_color_brewer(palette=12) +#color of title
  coord_polar(theta="y") +#change to circle
  xlim(c(-1, 4)) +#cut the center of the circle
  labs(title = "Distribution of the highest degree in universities in the US")+
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

#From this analysis visualization, we can state that most of collges are having the Master Degree,which is more than 82%

QUESTION 9: What is the distribution of Private and Public University?

library(sqldf)
data2<-sqldf("select region,control,count(control) as control_count from m group by region,control")
data3<-sqldf("select region,count(control) as control_sum from m group by region")
data4<-merge(data2,data3,by= "region")
data4$control_percent<-data4$control_count/data4$control_sum
data4$label1<-c("Midwest"," ","Northeast"," ","South"," ","West"," ")
data4$label2<-paste(data4$control,":\n",data4$control_count,"\n(",round(data4$control_percent*100,1),"%)")
head(data4)
##      region control control_count control_sum control_percent    label1
## 1   Midwest Private           246         353       0.6968839   Midwest
## 2   Midwest  Public           107         353       0.3031161          
## 3 Northeast Private           185         299       0.6187291 Northeast
## 4 Northeast  Public           114         299       0.3812709          
## 5     South Private           250         459       0.5446623     South
## 6     South  Public           209         459       0.4553377          
##                        label2
## 1 Private :\n 246 \n( 69.7 %)
## 2  Public :\n 107 \n( 30.3 %)
## 3 Private :\n 185 \n( 61.9 %)
## 4  Public :\n 114 \n( 38.1 %)
## 5 Private :\n 250 \n( 54.5 %)
## 6  Public :\n 209 \n( 45.5 %)
ggplot(data4, aes(x = region, y = control_percent, fill = control)) +
  geom_col() + # 
  geom_text(aes(label=label2),size=2.2,position=position_stack(vjust = 0.5))+
  geom_text(aes(label=label1),size=5,position = position_fill())+
  scale_x_discrete(limits = c(" "," "," ", "Midwest","Northeast","South","West")) +  #cut the center of the circle
  scale_fill_brewer(palette=3) +
  coord_polar("y")+                                                                  #change to circle
  labs(title = "Distribution of Private and Public Universities")+
  theme_void()+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

#We can see that the West side is not having a big difference between the private and public university regarding the chart. However, the South, Northeast and Midwest tend to have more private school than public college. This conclusion can interpret that maybe cause the South,Northeast, Midwest are having more Art or religion colleges than the West side.
